<!-- ══════════════ UX PRINCIPLES ══════════════ -->
<div class="doc-section" id="s-principles">
  <div class="principles-hero">
    <div class="pr-tag">UX Design Principles</div>
    <h1 class="pr-h">Design decisions<br>made <em>deliberately</em></h1>
    <p class="pr-sub">Every principle is derived from a specific observation — global best practice, competitor failure, or verified user behavior data. Nothing is decorative.</p>
    <div class="principles-grid">
      <div class="pr-card">
        <div class="pr-num">P.01</div>
        <h3 class="pr-h2">Results first.<br><em>Always.</em></h3>
        <p class="pr-p">NerdWallet removed its pre-qual quiz in 2024 after proving it caused 67% abandonment. Users arrive from Google with intent. Any friction before results is theft of their time. Show all products immediately. Filter inline.</p>
        <div class="pr-example">"You searched 'best cashback credit card'. Here are the top 8. Filter by your spend pattern below — no account needed."</div>
      </div>
      <div class="pr-card">
        <div class="pr-num">P.02</div>
        <h3 class="pr-h2">Predict, don't<br><em>just describe</em></h3>
        <p class="pr-p">Every product page should answer: "Will I get approved?" Show an approval probability ring on every card. Show an affordability score on every loan. ClearScore and NerdWallet built their user trust on this single mechanic.</p>
        <div class="pr-example">"Based on CIBIL 748: Approval Likely (82%). Your income supports EMI up to ₹18,400/month."</div>
      </div>
      <div class="pr-card">
        <div class="pr-num">P.03</div>
        <h3 class="pr-h2">Trust is the<br><em>primary feature</em></h3>
        <p class="pr-p">The editorial independence banner isn't a legal footer — it's a hero element. "We earn commission. Our rankings don't." This one line, placed prominently above every list, does more for conversion than any redesign.</p>
        <div class="pr-example">Green trust bar at top of every comparison page: "Our ranking methodology is independent. We earn commission — it never changes our order."</div>
      </div>
      <div class="pr-card">
        <div class="pr-num">P.04</div>
        <h3 class="pr-h2">One voice,<br><em>everywhere</em></h3>
        <p class="pr-p">MoneySavingExpert's entire brand is "Martin Lewis says." InvestingPro needs a named, photographed expert whose opinion appears on every category page. Not a generic disclaimer — a specific person the user can Google and trust.</p>
        <div class="pr-example">"InvestingPro's Take: The SBI Cashback card is genuinely the best for most Indians — but only if you never carry a balance. Here's why."</div>
      </div>
      <div class="pr-card">
        <div class="pr-num">P.05</div>
        <h3 class="pr-h2">Simulate, don't<br><em>just inform</em></h3>
        <p class="pr-p">Credit Karma's most-used feature is the credit score simulator. "What happens to my score if I pay off this card?" Nobody in India has built this. Interactive tools that simulate outcomes keep users 5x longer and convert at 3x the rate of static text.</p>
        <div class="pr-example">CIBIL Simulator: "If you pay ₹45K on your Axis card → CIBIL improves ~16 points in 60 days → You'd qualify for HDFC Infinia (currently 'Unlikely')"</div>
      </div>
      <div class="pr-card">
        <div class="pr-num">P.06</div>
        <h3 class="pr-h2">Cross-vertical<br><em>intelligence</em></h3>
        <p class="pr-p">InvestingPro's structural advantage over every competitor: a Section 80C page that links to ELSS, PPF, NPS, and the 80C calculator. ClearTax can't do this. Paisabazaar barely does. Every page should offer at least 2 intelligent cross-vertical connections.</p>
        <div class="pr-example">On home loan page: "Paying ₹1.5L principal this year? That's also your full 80C deduction. Here are the ELSS funds you can skip."</div>
      </div>
      <div class="pr-card">
        <div class="pr-num">P.07</div>
        <h3 class="pr-h2">Build direct traffic.<br><em>Own the channel.</em></h3>
        <p class="pr-p">MoneySavingExpert's 9M email subscribers mean they don't live and die by Google. InvestingPro Weekly — sent every Monday — should become InvestingPro's primary moat. Every page has one email CTA. No popups. One clean, consistent ask.</p>
        <div class="pr-example">Footer of every page: "Get InvestingPro Weekly. Rate changes, new card launches, tax reminders. 60 seconds every Monday. No spam, ever."</div>
      </div>
      <div class="pr-card">
        <div class="pr-num">P.08</div>
        <h3 class="pr-h2">Density with<br><em>breathing room</em></h3>
        <p class="pr-p">Financial data is inherently dense. The solution isn't to remove data — it's to create clear visual hierarchy so users can scan to what matters and pause where they need to think. Generous whitespace around decisions, controlled density in data.</p>
        <div class="pr-example">Card comparison rows: tight data in the center, generous padding around the apply button, visual weight concentrated on the one thing the user needs to do next.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="pr-card">
        <div class="pr-num">P.09</div>
        <h3 class="pr-h2">The <em>honest</em><br>downside</h3>
        <p class="pr-p">Every card recommendation should include one honest caveat. "This card is brilliant — unless you ever miss a payment, in which case you'll pay 42% annual interest." Users who receive honest caveats trust the recommendations 4x more than pure promotional copy.</p>
        <div class="pr-example">"The catch: reward points expire in 12 months and the redemption process takes 3–5 working days. Factor this in before applying."</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

